    "abstract": "Abstract: This paper examines a model of delegated investment within a noisy rational expectations equilibrium framework. Portfolio managers can acquire costly signals about asset payoffs but incur portfolio management costs. They are compensated by delegating investors and make investment decisions on their behalf. The optimal contract features a benchmark component that helps mitigate agency frictions arising from these management costs. The precision of the private signals chosen by managers is determined endogenously through market equilibrium. Private and public signals act as substitutes. When portfolio management costs increase, both the performance and benchmark components of the optimal contract rise, however fewer private signals are incorporated into the public signal, reducing the informational efficiency of prices. When a social planner places sufficient weight on the welfare of direct investors or liquidity providers, the socially optimal equilibrium yields greater price informational efficiency compared to the decentralized equilibrium.",
